            }
          ]
        },
        "capped": false
      }
    ],
    "search_count": 1,
    "final_answer": "**Penicillin was discovered by Scottish physician **Alexander Fleming**** in **1928**.\n\nWhile working at St. Mary's Hospital in London, Fleming observed that a *Penicillium* mould (later identified as *Penicillium rubens*) was secreting a substance that inhibited the growth of bacteria. He named this substance **\"penicillin.\"** The mould had contaminated a bacterial culture in his laboratory, leading to this landmark discovery.\n\nHowever, the full development of penicillin as a usable medicine came later. In **1939**, a team of scientists at the University of Oxford \u2014 led by **Howard Florey** and including **Ernst Chain**, **Norman Heatley**, and others \u2014 developed methods to extract, purify, and mass-produce penicillin, making it available as a life-saving antibiotic. Fleming, Florey, and Chain were jointly awarded the **Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1945** for this work.",
